nstrates how CBPR can be effectively applied to archaeology. Drawing on her own experiences with research projects in North America and the Near East, Atalay provides theoretical discussions along with practical examples of establishing and developing collaborative relationships and sharing results. This book will contribute to building an archaeology that is engaged, ethical, relevant, and sustainable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArchaeologyxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aArchaeologyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCommunity archaeologyxUnited States. 0aCommunity archaeologyzUnited States. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionzUnited States. 0aIndians of North AmericaxAntiquitiesxConservation and restoration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520953468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520953468.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles